segments.text: I did not do well in Frigg, that pole.
How big were the classes?
Well, in that class, it would have been 25 or 30, probably.
But none of these huge ones?
Not in Frigg.
Now, in chemistry,
Well, in organic chemistry, that was a large, very large lecture.
The lecture part was large, and then we broke up, you know, and recitation was a somewhat smaller class.
Did you have any of the legendary faculty member teachers that freshman year?
I can't remember the name of the guy in Trigg, but
I've always felt that his approach was not helpful for me because he really expected you to get it yourself, as a student, I mean.
He just left you.
Floundering right now routine of the day described a class day a typical routine y'all got up at 6 6 30 Fill out went to went to chow.
Yeah in the morning and back to through the room pick up books and go go to class and
And did you fall out for lunch?
Yes, we fell out for each meal.
We had meal formation.
Thursday afternoons were all TC or drill anyway.
And where did y'all drill?
My freshman year, we drilled on the, in the area,
by Welburn Road, and also in that open area between Walton, just due west of Sabeasa.
That was our basic area to drill.
Then come back and get ready for our evening chow.

then did you come back to your dorm room every night for study yeah uh where did could you or any other fish escape from that routine during the day where could you kind of hide out relax well we had the uh see the memorial student center was new and uh
That was a popular place.
Also, you could go to Guyon Hall and go to the movies in the afternoon.
In the afternoon?
Mm-hmm.
Oh, I didn't know they had afternoon movies.
Well, maybe this was on the weekend.
Okay.
Because I didn't go except on the weekend, I can think.
And did you all go to the library?
I think maybe it was just a Saturday.
Did you go to the library as a hideout?
during the day?
Sometimes, uh-huh.
But we had a pretty small library at that time.
If you were sleepy and wanted to take a nap, where could you do that?
The library was probably the safest place, but that was not something.
I know that that's something that some of the students would do, but that wasn't my forte, I guess.
Typical behavior in class.
Did you all go to class regularly?
Were you wide awake?
Yeah, except after lunch.
Well, in the summertime, especially.
No, but in the long semesters.
In the long semester, yeah.
Well, I have much less recall of classes.
I remember animal husbandry, 107.
I remember that class because it was from my background.
I had just been looking forward.
having a real easy class.
Surely there would be one that would be really interesting and really easy, and so I'd look forward to that.
Boy, it was pretty tough.
Maurice Shelton was teaching it.
Maurice retired from the Texas Agricultural Experiment Station out at San Angelo, goat specialist.
But Maurice was finishing his PhD, so he was really a keen sort of an individual.
And he just, man, he really worked us.
Did that add to your veterinary medicine desire?

that course well it helped focus it a little bit i had as i remember that was something that i i did find that aspect refreshing that at least i was getting to be around animals a little bit and uh so that that was helping because all of this other would have been
pretty foreign to veterinary medicine as far as I could see.
I couldn't understand why in the world a veterinarian had needed to do all of this stuff.
You know, typical college freshman.
And you never thought about changing your major?
Not that year.
But see, we're getting to a point now at the end of this semester because of my problem with organic chemistry and that intrigue.
I became had become pretty frustrated with academia and when I went home at Christmas time of course this was not the end of the semester this was a Christmas break talked to some
guys about my age out there that were really hauling it in, working in the oil field.
And so I just decided that, well, at the very least I needed to work, try that for a while.
And I could always go back to school in the fall and I'd still be on schedule.

and so i i laid out after oh you dropped out i dropped out of school my dad really tongue-lashed me and my mother cried you know did did you talk to anybody here and no advisor or anything here about whether or not that was a good idea you decided it and did you stay at home yeah i lived at home and worked uh went to work for uh
a roustabout company that was owned by Dr. John Milliff's brother.
I didn't know that at the time, of course, that they were.
What kind of big money did you make?
Well, I made, starting as a roustabout, I think I made $1.10 an hour, which was really pretty good.
And I was able to put in a lot of hours.

And before then in the summer, after, well, maybe this isn't about school, but see, I had made this decision that I was going to lay out and take a look at the oil business as a life, you know, occupation.
and so I did and I got this job with this this roustabout company and my first morning the first task that that my crew had was to string a water line for a well that was to be drilled
out in a new oil field that was being developed between Winters and Coleman.
And they got me up, woke me up about four o'clock that morning, and it was snowing.
And we went out, there were four of us in the cab of this truck, just sitting on top of one another, everybody except the driver.
And we had a load of, it was a semi-truck loaded with pipe that was to be two-inch pipe that was to be, I didn't know it at the time, but we were going to scatter it over this rocky terrain.
And the first step was for someone to walk along behind and grab one of them and pull it off as the truck
kind of winded its way across this ranch land.
And then we would come back and join them together, you know, and do it that way.
Well, guess who got to unload the pipe?
The new guy on the crew.
And so that was a real jolt to me, you know, reality, a lesson in reality.
I mean, this was not what I thought working in the oil field would be like.
nearly froze to death that morning.
And so you did that for spring and summer.
In the summer I started roughnecking.
Got a job working on a drilling rig and making a dollar fifty an hour, you know.
And I thought long and hard about staying with that company.
It was a drilling company out of Fort Worth and they wanted me to stay.

and of course naturally they would as I look back on it because it was real hard to find workers all right and but then anyway I think one of the biggest things influences was my mother's crying and she was not a person that did that often but I knew that it
I had really disappointed her by laying out, so I did come back to A&M to start my sophomore year.
Right, and you're back in the Corps, and you are a few hours behind being a sophomore?
No, I had 30, maybe 32 hours.
I did, I should have had 36, I think.
But I... You're back in the Corps.
Uh-huh.
In the same outfit?
No, but I cannot remember.
It was a squadron over in the, in the regular Corps area.
What kind of a sophomore were you in your relations with the fish?
Well, I thought I was pretty benign, but I've had, there were two or three that I had went to class with, two or three freshmen who went to class with me in botany class that thought that I was
Pretty tough sophomore.
And how were you fairly sure that you were taking the right classes that sophomore year to be sure you were going to be ready for vet school?
Who advised you?
I did not have a...
contact with the vet school until the spring semester.
So you're still on your own.
So I guess I'm still in general studies.
And I just do not have the name, you know, there's not a name there that was influential.
Was it better to be a sophomore in the Corps than it had been to be a freshman?
Yeah, much better in that
Of course, at that point, when I came back, I had my own agenda pretty well set in my mind as to what I was going to do and how it was going to be.
And I had resolved that it was veterinary medicine over the Corps.
And so I would participate in the Corps and meet my obligations, but I wasn't going to get
caught up in it.
I think I had to a certain extent as a freshman.
It had become something of a diversion.
What did you do with all of that money that you had made as a Love Hill employee?
Well, it didn't last very long.
You didn't have a car?
Yeah, yeah.
Oh.
I came back with a 1941 Club Coupe Pontiac.
Sure did.
And the average student didn't have a car then.
That's right.
Yeah.
And I remember two things with that Club Coupe Pontiac.
One was, it was the only car I ever had where the universal joint broke on the drive shaft, you know.
Talk about a helpless feeling.
But that happened.
out in the open highway between here and Winters.
And the other was brake line leakage, you know, the old rubber diaphragms at each wheel, one of those that come off.
And we had gone uptown to, up into downtown Bryan to the, I guess, the Palace of the Queen and gone to a movie.
There were myself and...
two or three buddies.
And we started back and coming out South College, and I had not even checked the brake pedal, I guess, until the traffic light there at Hillcrest.
This is a, not Colter.
Oh, there's a mobile station there.
Now, there's a Hillcrest grocery store that's been there for a long time.
But anyway, there was a traffic light there then, and there still is.
And I put on the brake, and there was nothing.
I never will forget that sensation either.
Did you hit anything?
No.
But I remember
I just remember turning left onto that street, whatever the name of it is, that goes on down to what eventually then where Townshire eventually was built.
During those years, as far as you and your buddies were aware, were there any Crip courses, any easy giveaway courses?
Well, you know,
The major, a major that was generally regarded as kind of sniffed at by a lot of the other majors was business administration.
If you were a BA major, that usually did not.
That was supposed to be easy.
Yeah, that was supposedly an easy major.
I don't know whether that was true or not.
As far as you and your buddies were aware, were there any giveaway courses for athletes?
Well, I don't know.
You know, this is one of the things that I've been thinking about as I was reflecting back.
One of the things I'd forgotten from a long time ago was that
You know, we used to have valedictorian, a stated valedictorian here, at least through the time it was an A&M college.
Now, I don't know when that practice might have stopped.
But the valedictorian of the class of 52 was a football player.
And he was a .
I mean, he was a sharp guy.
And something else.
that I think is different about that, well, that we saw at that time was that about a fourth or so of the members, the inductees into Who's Who in America, American colleges, would be athletes.
Now this is not, I don't think this reflects
catering to them so much as it did that there were some pretty top flight individuals as individuals that were, they were athletes and they were also scholars and they were also leaders.
Who were the, were there some famous students when you were an undergraduate?
that everybody knew who they were when they walked down the sidewalk?
Well, yeah.
In my freshman year, of course, Bob Smith was an All-American running back or fullback.
I can't remember which.
But everybody recognized him.
Darryl Hooper, Olympian, and also a football player.
Now, were they in uniform during the day?
I've seen, yeah, I've seen both of them in uniform now, but I've also seen them not in uniform during the day.
Were they?
They generally, when you saw them out of uniform in non-reg, when you saw them non-reg, it was usually
between Hart Hall and the athletic complex.
And as far as y'all remember, those highly, those famous athletes were pleasant students.
They said hello and they chatted with other people.
Yeah, there were, I found that,
impressive.
I see there was a, what was the guy's name, he was a basketball player that made an honorable mention in All America, I think.
And he was just a very approachable, just a very outgoing sort of a guy.
Now Bob Smith was pretty aloof.
I remember, one of the things I remember is going to a movie at the campus theater,
One night, I can't remember what the movie was.
It was full.
There was some, I guess it was a special movie or something.
And Bob Smith came in after the house was pretty well packed.
The lights were still on, though.
And his date was one Miss Harrison, Dick Harrison's sister.
And I think maybe they married eventually.
But she was an eye-catcher, too, and a lot of catcall-type things, you know.
And during that sophomore year, you and your buddies were involved in all kinds of the traditions.
What was silver taps like for you when you first attended?
Very, very...
somber occasions, really, really emotional to me.
Touched your feelings?
Yeah.
What about Bonfire?
What was Bonfire effort like then?
How long did you and your buddies work on it?
Seemed like forever.
Really?
In that particular era of time,
Of course the bonfire, I guess, it was kind of looked on as a freshman endeavor and a senior endeavor.
Those were the two classes that seemed to have some identity with any given bonfire.
And so we, our bonfire, our fish bonfire was built
on the, across from the MSC there.
Drill field?
Drill field.
And it was the TP type that we're going back to, I think.
And no mechanization, none.
You know, I mean, everything was done by hand and slave labor type.
Long lines of students with huge ropes, you know.
Did you, were you in the cut area or the stack area?
Both.
I worked more in the stack area than I did at the cut area.
Do you remember, was it rainy?
It was weeks.
It was weeks of effort.
Yeah, as I remember now, when I say it seemed like forever, I understand that was with everything else that was going on.
And no serious injuries.
Not that I recall.
Right, then yell practice.
At the Grove, yeah, we went to yell practice.
See, then we had yell practice.
You left the dining room and went to yell practice twice a week.
Was there also a midnight yell practice the night before the game in the stadium?
I don't remember it.
See, I don't think there was.
I don't think so.
Do you remember going to Muster as an undergraduate?
Yeah, but it was, as an upperclassman, quite...
I believe that was my...
Fifth year here, the year before I finished vet school.
Describe your freshman year.
You all did go through final review and all that.
Well, my freshman year in the spring.
Oh, that you were here, yeah.
As your sophomore, you went through all of that.
Yeah, I went through.
But I have very little recollection of it.
Did you and your buddies attend the social events, the dances and all that?
Some of them, yeah.
And did you have some dates?
Yeah.
Where'd you get your date from?
Well, TWU, and then there were, I dated, had dates with local girls two or three times.
Where'd you meet them?
church, and at that time I was, well it was the Baptist Student Union, that was the college.
And that was an important Sunday night event, wasn't it?
Yeah, yeah, and it was.
Because there was food.
And girls.
And girls.
And no hazing.
Yeah.
Held at the North Gate.
Yeah.
Do you remember Religious Emphasis Week?
Yeah, very well.
What was that like?
Well, it was hectic in that everything, you know, if you attended these, many of the events, like in the dorms, and I remember, not my sophomore,
Well, my sophomore year, we had a series leader, and I was in dorm two.
And dorm two was one of the dorms that had a lounge area.
And so that's where one of the religious week series was held.
I can't tell you what was discussed, but I remember it.
The thing I remember about it was that it was thought-provoking.
And I must say that up to that point, you know, I really hadn't given any depth of thought to religious matters.
So that religious emphasis week did have some positive results for you.
Yeah, it sure did.
My sophomore and...
I guess I was more affected or more, I participated more or attended more my sophomore, junior, and senior years.
Now, went to movies at Guyon Hall.
Were there other events?
There were programs, the equivalent of Opus.
Okay.
This was a student.
Do you remember any famous?
Town Hall was just started, I guess, probably.
Guyon was still- Do you remember any famous celebrities that came to perform?
Joni James and- Were the big bands still coming for the dances?
Yeah, we had some of the dances.
I can't remember- And G. Raleigh was already built?
G. Raleigh White?
He was built in 56, I think.
Oh, really?
So we're still over.
We were at DeWare.
At DeWare.
Describe going to an Aggie football game.
What was the routine on a Saturday?
Y'all went to class all morning.
We had class in the morning, yeah, and...
And we just keyed on when we had to fall in formation to go to the game, to march into the game.
And you did a march in.
Yeah.
And if you had a date, you met her in the stadium?
Because she couldn't march in with you.
That's right.
And then what happened during the games for you fish and sophomores?
Just lots of yelling.
I don't think, while I was in the Corps, I don't think I had a day to do any games.
Then when it was over, did you and your buddies participate in?
As freshmen, we participated in hauling the yell leaders out.
Then what did you all do on a Saturday night after a game?
Oh, a big thing for us was just to not eat at the channel, go to North Gate or something like that.
As a freshman, I remember we'd eat at one of the North Gate places, which, boy, were certainly not, that wasn't a memorable experience at all.
All right, now, if somebody really wanted to party in those days, those nights, where did they go?
